1
00:01:31,049 --> 00:01:32,721
Here, Charlie. More fortune cookies.

2
00:01:32,808 --> 00:01:34,561
- Good luck!
- Thanks! What?

3
00:01:34,649 --> 00:01:39,278
Next week, we'll be selling
Sanyo remote control VCRs for $299!

4
00:01:39,368 --> 00:01:41,837
- Look, it's Dad!
- Oh, no! I'll go broke!

5
00:01:42,049 --> 00:01:47,076
To give away Mitsubishi
giant-screen television sets for $1,299!

6
00:01:47,248 --> 00:01:48,840
Oh, no!

7
00:01:48,929 --> 00:01:53,956
We won't be undersold on microwaves,
videorecorders, ovens...

8
00:01:54,129 --> 00:01:57,325
- Mom, you're not looking.
- Please turn that off.

9
00:01:57,849 --> 00:02:00,203
Mom, when are you going to stop
being mad at Dad?

10
00:02:00,289 --> 00:02:02,722
I mean, how do you think
that makes me feel?

11
00:02:02,808 --> 00:02:05,801
I have certain unresolved feelings
about your father.

12
00:02:06,168 --> 00:02:07,567
I don't trust him.

13
00:02:08,449 --> 00:02:11,485
- And I hate those commercials.
- All right, forget it.

14
00:02:11,568 --> 00:02:13,639
We don't have time
for another heart-to-heart.

15
00:02:13,729 --> 00:02:15,401
Come on. You have to get dressed.

16
00:02:18,968 --> 00:02:22,405
- I want you to understand it's insulting...
- Watch your hair.

17
00:02:23,049 --> 00:02:27,326
...for him to go from me to that bimbo.
Do you think he really loves Janet?

18
00:02:28,088 --> 00:02:30,318
Maybe he's just smashed
too many fortune cookies!

19
00:02:30,408 --> 00:02:33,287
Mom, give me a break!
He's missing the reunion because of you.

20
00:02:33,368 --> 00:02:35,086
You know he's dying to go.

21
00:02:35,769 --> 00:02:38,329
At least we won't both have
a miserable time.

22
00:02:40,848 --> 00:02:42,168
Let me see.

23
00:02:42,568 --> 00:02:44,206
What do you think?

24
00:02:44,489 --> 00:02:46,319
You are a very hip chick!

25
00:02:46,769 --> 00:02:49,966
God, you look like you've stepped
right out of Life magazine!

26
00:02:50,248 --> 00:02:51,283
I don't know.

27
00:02:51,368 --> 00:02:53,836
What if nobody else there
is dressed like this?

28
00:02:53,929 --> 00:02:54,963
So?

29
00:02:55,769 --> 00:02:57,441
- I don't think I wanna go.
- Mom.

30
00:02:57,528 --> 00:03:01,044
Everybody's just gonna say,
"Well, hey, where's Crazy Charlie?"

31
00:03:01,808 --> 00:03:04,368
Lots of people are separated and divorced.

32
00:03:05,769 --> 00:03:07,998
Not from the guy
with the lowest prices in town.

33
00:03:09,489 --> 00:03:12,002
I feel ridiculous in this dress!
I'd like to change.

34
00:03:12,088 --> 00:03:14,158
Why are you so nervous?
What's the matter?

35
00:03:14,248 --> 00:03:16,399
Reunions do funny things
to people at this age.

36
00:03:16,489 --> 00:03:18,639
- Hi, Peggy Sue! Beth!
- Hi.

37
00:03:19,769 --> 00:03:20,837
Hi, Maddy.

38
00:03:21,368 --> 00:03:22,437
How are you?

39
00:03:22,528 --> 00:03:24,485
You two look
just like that soap commercial.

40
00:03:24,568 --> 00:03:27,800
- "Which one's the mother?"
- "And which one's the daughter?"

41
00:03:29,209 --> 00:03:32,598
You took this seriously.
You're a real blast from the past!

42
00:03:33,049 --> 00:03:34,687
It was Beth's idea.

43
00:03:34,808 --> 00:03:38,085
I wish I had the nerve. And the figure.

44
00:03:38,329 --> 00:03:41,002
- Hi.
- Hi! Peggy Sue Bodell?

45
00:03:41,088 --> 00:03:43,125
- All right.
- Mom?

46
00:03:43,609 --> 00:03:45,360
Beth's boyfriend is with the band.

47
00:03:45,449 --> 00:03:47,439
- Must run in the family.
- What does?

48
00:03:47,528 --> 00:03:50,680
You and your mother.
You both seem to fall for musicians.

49
00:04:00,889 --> 00:04:02,207
Mom, look!

50
00:04:03,128 --> 00:04:04,402
Oh, God!

51
00:04:05,528 --> 00:04:08,680
It's okay. Come on. Look!

52
00:04:11,008 --> 00:04:13,842
Why don't you find a table?
We'll see you in a little while.

53
00:04:13,929 --> 00:04:14,918
Sure.

54
00:04:15,329 --> 00:04:19,641
God, Mom, that picture's great!
Come on, let's get a table.

55
00:04:33,569 --> 00:04:35,240
- Is this good?
- Fine.

56
00:04:35,329 --> 00:04:38,161
- I'll be right back. You be all right?
- Sure.

57
00:04:38,249 --> 00:04:41,321
Thank you. We're gonna do
a little medley for you now.

58
00:04:45,649 --> 00:04:49,163
- Come on, pose like your picture.
- What?

59
00:04:52,329 --> 00:04:54,319
Hi, do you like it?

60
00:04:54,408 --> 00:04:57,958
I figured as everyone has a gold Rolex,
I'd have one made in platinum.

61
00:04:58,048 --> 00:05:00,608
- What a wonderful idea!
- How are you?

62
00:05:00,689 --> 00:05:02,838
I'm fine. How many children do you have?

63
00:05:02,928 --> 00:05:05,283
- I don't have any.
- You don't? I thought you did.

64
00:05:05,369 --> 00:05:07,485
- No. How many do you have?
- I have four.

65
00:05:07,569 --> 00:05:08,718
- Four?
- Four, yeah.

66
00:05:08,809 --> 00:05:10,083
I'm so happy for you.

67
00:05:10,168 --> 00:05:12,204
- I love them so much.
- How's Peggy Sue doing?

68
00:05:12,288 --> 00:05:14,199
She was a mess,
right after they separated.

69
00:05:14,288 --> 00:05:17,247
But I think she's coming out of it.
Seems to be friendly now.

70
00:05:17,329 --> 00:05:18,523
I'm so glad.

71
00:05:19,288 --> 00:05:21,279
Sometimes it's easier when you hate them.

72
00:05:21,649 --> 00:05:24,721
- How about a little dance, princess?
- Walter!

73
00:05:25,728 --> 00:05:27,764
- How are you?
- Good.

74
00:05:28,168 --> 00:05:30,728
- Nice to see you. I'll see you later.
- Yeah.

75
00:05:31,649 --> 00:05:33,685
Aren't you Peggy Sue Kelcher?

76
00:05:33,769 --> 00:05:38,524
I was once. Richard Norvik?

77
00:05:40,488 --> 00:05:42,240
I didn't recognise you!

78
00:05:42,329 --> 00:05:45,206
You look terrific.
You look exactly the same.

79
00:05:45,288 --> 00:05:48,122
I feel ridiculous!
I only did this for tonight, you know.

80
00:05:48,209 --> 00:05:50,120
- It's adorable.
- Thank you.

81
00:05:50,209 --> 00:05:52,927
Peggy Sue Kelcher, this is my wife, Sharon.

82
00:05:53,009 --> 00:05:56,718
- How nice to meet you. Why don't you sit?
- Thank you.

83
00:05:56,809 --> 00:05:59,528
But call me Peggy. Peggy Bodell now.

84
00:06:00,249 --> 00:06:02,319
So, where's Charlie?

85
00:06:02,769 --> 00:06:07,240
I was in town about a year ago
and I turn on the television...

86
00:06:07,329 --> 00:06:10,081
...and I see Crazy Charlie.

87
00:06:10,689 --> 00:06:12,485
It really made me laugh.

88
00:06:13,249 --> 00:06:15,319
Charlie won't be here tonight.

89
00:06:17,408 --> 00:06:21,959
- We're getting divorced, actually.
- I'm sorry to hear that.

90
00:06:22,209 --> 00:06:24,927
Mr. Norvik!

91
00:06:25,009 --> 00:06:27,728
Richard. Doug Snell, Merrill Lynch.

92
00:06:28,728 --> 00:06:32,562
I read about that Codex deal
in Business Week. Congratulations!

93
00:06:33,088 --> 00:06:35,125
Thank you very much.

94
00:06:35,369 --> 00:06:39,442
Peggy, how are you? How's Charlie?
Hey, Terry!

95
00:06:39,689 --> 00:06:42,202
- Thank you, Doug, thank you very much.
- Call me.

96
00:06:42,528 --> 00:06:45,805
Madeline Hutton and Arthur Nagle
were high school sweethearts.

97
00:06:45,889 --> 00:06:49,086
Married right after graduation,
they're still together.

98
00:06:49,249 --> 00:06:54,322
Maddy. Arthur. How does it feel
to have missed the sexual revolution?

99
00:06:54,649 --> 00:06:57,004
What? What kind of question is that?

100
00:06:57,088 --> 00:06:59,887
That doesn't have anything to do
with the reunion, Delores!

101
00:06:59,968 --> 00:07:01,197
Take it easy, kitten.

102
00:07:03,369 --> 00:07:06,805
- Welcome to the singles scene.
- I don't know how you do it.

103
00:07:07,488 --> 00:07:09,956
I've never even dated anybody but Charlie.

104
00:07:10,689 --> 00:07:12,360
It's not that bad, really.

105
00:07:12,449 --> 00:07:16,487
You just have to think of men like houses,
and trade upward.

106
00:07:19,129 --> 00:07:23,122
I always thought that you and Charlie
had a really great marriage.

107
00:07:23,809 --> 00:07:25,127
I think we did.

108
00:07:26,209 --> 00:07:27,800
We just got married too young...

109
00:07:27,889 --> 00:07:31,358
...and ended up blaming each other
for all the things we missed.

110
00:07:31,569 --> 00:07:35,403
So he started having affairs
and you started getting depressed?

111
00:07:37,608 --> 00:07:40,567
You just should have left here years ago,
like I did.

112
00:07:40,889 --> 00:07:42,288
It's not so bad.

113
00:07:42,848 --> 00:07:46,158
I've got two great kids.
I've got my own business.

114
00:07:48,088 --> 00:07:52,081
Still, if I knew then what I know now...

115
00:07:53,408 --> 00:07:55,684
...l'd do a lot of things differently.

116
00:07:56,288 --> 00:07:58,927
Your damn computers
put me out of business.

117
00:07:59,048 --> 00:08:00,163
You're right. He's drunk.

118
00:08:00,249 --> 00:08:02,557
You're a billionaire
and I'm a goddamn failure.

119
00:08:03,288 --> 00:08:05,086
No, the bakery's doing very well.

120
00:08:05,168 --> 00:08:08,161
- Do you manage it?
- I own it.

121
00:08:08,728 --> 00:08:10,401
I remember that dress.

122
00:08:12,968 --> 00:08:14,482
Rosalie?

123
00:08:16,088 --> 00:08:19,286
Oh, no. I remember that locket, too.

124
00:08:19,728 --> 00:08:23,721
You were so excited!
I think you showed it to the whole school.

125
00:08:23,809 --> 00:08:25,367
You have an incredible memory.

126
00:08:25,449 --> 00:08:28,406
- It's beautiful. Does it open?
- Yes.

127
00:08:29,968 --> 00:08:33,166
- These are my children.
- They're so cute!

128
00:08:33,249 --> 00:08:35,284
Of course, they're not babies anymore!

129
00:08:35,369 --> 00:08:38,087
But you were married
when you were three, right?

130
00:08:38,808 --> 00:08:40,400
God bless you!

131
00:08:45,448 --> 00:08:47,678
The best thing about being a dentist.

132
00:08:48,089 --> 00:08:49,807
Pure pharmaceutical grade.

133
00:08:50,208 --> 00:08:53,280
A couple of lines of this,
I could drill my own teeth.

134
00:08:58,168 --> 00:08:59,203
Hi.

135
00:09:01,129 --> 00:09:02,118
Hi.

136
00:09:09,129 --> 00:09:12,166
- Who's the guy with the eyes?
- Michael Fitzsimmons.

137
00:09:12,649 --> 00:09:14,957
I used to have
such a crush on him in school.

138
00:09:15,048 --> 00:09:16,721
- Peggy.
- Hi!

139
00:09:16,849 --> 00:09:19,124
God, that Walter Getz can still dance!

140
00:09:20,489 --> 00:09:24,277
Your first boyfriend!
Come on, tell me. Any sparks left?

141
00:09:24,369 --> 00:09:25,768
Well, who knows?

142
00:09:25,849 --> 00:09:28,841
I mean, remember,
whatever Walter wants...

143
00:09:28,928 --> 00:09:30,965
...Walter gets!

144
00:09:34,089 --> 00:09:35,841
I'm sorry. Sharon Norvik.

145
00:09:36,249 --> 00:09:40,400
This is Carol Heath and Maddy Nagle,
my oldest and my dearest friends.

146
00:09:40,489 --> 00:09:42,878
- Nice to meet you.
- Sharon is married to Richard.

147
00:09:42,969 --> 00:09:44,527
- Lucky lady!
- Thank you.

148
00:09:44,609 --> 00:09:46,918
Michael Fitzsimmons. Is he here?

149
00:09:47,448 --> 00:09:50,407
No. No, I asked Rosalie.
She couldn't track him down.

150
00:09:50,489 --> 00:09:53,322
- That's too bad.
- He must have been quite a guy.

151
00:09:53,408 --> 00:09:54,318
Yeah.

152
00:09:55,328 --> 00:09:59,322
You know, he is the only boy in high school
I wish I'd gone to bed with!

153
00:09:59,408 --> 00:10:00,682
Only one?

154
00:10:01,568 --> 00:10:03,798
Well, besides Charlie.

155
00:10:09,369 --> 00:10:11,279
I hope the sales of your book go very well.

156
00:10:11,369 --> 00:10:13,438
Anything anecdotal
you'd like to leave us with?

157
00:10:13,528 --> 00:10:15,565
Yeah, every dog has its day.

158
00:10:15,649 --> 00:10:16,798
Meaning what?

159
00:10:16,889 --> 00:10:21,041
Peggy, would you please rescue Richard?
Ask him to dance.

160
00:10:21,129 --> 00:10:23,722
Richard. Would you like to dance?

161
00:10:23,808 --> 00:10:26,277
Of course I would.
So, are we through now?

162
00:10:26,369 --> 00:10:27,484
- No.
- Good.

163
00:10:28,729 --> 00:10:30,798
From snivelling runt
to pompous ass in 25 years.

164
00:10:30,889 --> 00:10:32,606
That's quite an accomplishment.

165
00:10:39,328 --> 00:10:41,558
I really cannot get over this.

166
00:10:41,928 --> 00:10:45,477
The only time people like Delores Dodge
used to pay any attention to me...

167
00:10:45,568 --> 00:10:48,447
...was to laugh at me or insult me.

168
00:10:48,528 --> 00:10:50,360
- You know that guy Doug Snell?
- Yeah.

169
00:10:50,448 --> 00:10:52,837
He shook my hand
when we walked in here?

170
00:10:52,928 --> 00:10:55,044
He used to call me, "Four-eyed worm."

171
00:10:56,448 --> 00:10:58,120
You showed them all.

172
00:10:58,208 --> 00:11:00,881
You're rich and famous and successful...

173
00:11:02,249 --> 00:11:04,205
...and you have a beautiful wife.

174
00:11:04,288 --> 00:11:07,964
You were always friendly to me.
I appreciated that.

175
00:11:28,889 --> 00:11:31,767
It's Crazy Charlie, the appliance king!

176
00:11:32,009 --> 00:11:33,760
Hey, Charlie!

177
00:11:35,649 --> 00:11:38,640
Look at you! You're putting on
a little weight, man!

178
00:11:38,889 --> 00:11:40,845
You look great. Great.

179
00:11:41,408 --> 00:11:45,721
So, this is the reunion? It's wonderful.

180
00:11:45,808 --> 00:11:47,037
Like, wonderful!

181
00:11:47,129 --> 00:11:50,201
Are you and Peggy still talking?
I mean, is it amicable?

182
00:11:50,288 --> 00:11:52,404
She hasn't changed at all, Charlie.

183
00:11:52,568 --> 00:11:55,561
- Your daughter's a real doll.
- "Why, I oughta..."

184
00:12:18,729 --> 00:12:19,717
Hello.

185
00:12:22,568 --> 00:12:24,321
Hello!

186
00:12:24,969 --> 00:12:29,246
Can I have your attention, please?
Listen up! Can I have your attention?

187
00:12:29,408 --> 00:12:31,923
I know everybody's having a great time...

188
00:12:32,048 --> 00:12:36,246
...but now, you have to get ready for
that moment you've all been waiting for.

189
00:12:39,688 --> 00:12:41,441
Dad? Hi.

190
00:12:44,849 --> 00:12:48,443
The Reunion Committee has selected
a king and a queen.

191
00:12:55,928 --> 00:12:57,282
Let's get back to business.

192
00:12:57,369 --> 00:13:00,360
The Reunion Committee
has given this a lot of thought...

193
00:13:00,448 --> 00:13:04,488
...and decided on two people
who best represent the spirit...

194
00:13:04,568 --> 00:13:07,402
...of Buchanan High's Class of '60!

195
00:13:08,089 --> 00:13:09,567
What are you doing?

196
00:13:09,649 --> 00:13:12,640
The king is someone who,
in more ways than one...

197
00:13:12,729 --> 00:13:15,687
...has come a long way since he left here...

198
00:13:15,769 --> 00:13:18,919
...and we are especially proud
to welcome him back.

199
00:13:19,249 --> 00:13:22,081
Richard Norvik!
Come on up here, King Richard!

200
00:13:37,769 --> 00:13:39,804
I demand a recount!

201
00:13:42,969 --> 00:13:44,481
That's gotta be Getz!

202
00:13:45,448 --> 00:13:47,565
First you gotta learn how to count.

203
00:13:50,089 --> 00:13:52,239
Hold me back!

204
00:13:54,568 --> 00:13:56,684
Well, I just want to say thank you.

205
00:13:57,328 --> 00:14:01,799
Sharon and I feel real welcome.
We're having a great time.

206
00:14:02,528 --> 00:14:05,168
Boy, our high school
looks really good from up here.

207
00:14:05,249 --> 00:14:09,162
And I just wanna say, it's good to be back.
Thanks a lot.

208
00:14:16,489 --> 00:14:20,163
- Now, every king deserves a queen.
- Over here!

209
00:14:20,688 --> 00:14:22,360
Not you, Getz!

210
00:14:22,928 --> 00:14:24,327
Life of the party!

211
00:14:25,089 --> 00:14:27,080
But when we sent out the invitations...

212
00:14:27,168 --> 00:14:30,285
...we didn't mention anything about
this being a costume party...

213
00:14:30,369 --> 00:14:32,006
...and perhaps we should've...

214
00:14:32,089 --> 00:14:34,886
...because just looking at her
brings it all back!

215
00:14:34,969 --> 00:14:37,607
Ladies and gentlemen,
I give you our queen...

216
00:14:37,688 --> 00:14:41,807
...Peggy Sue Kelcher Bodell!
Come on up here, Peggy Sue!

217
00:14:42,369 --> 00:14:44,599
I can't. I can't do it.

218
00:14:44,808 --> 00:14:46,162
Yes, you can.

219
00:14:46,448 --> 00:14:50,806
Go on, you can do it. Go on.
You can do it.

220
00:15:17,568 --> 00:15:18,888
Congratulations.

221
00:15:27,328 --> 00:15:29,604
Thank you, thank you very much.

222
00:16:09,168 --> 00:16:10,238
Mom!

223
00:16:33,369 --> 00:16:35,599
Now, hold your arm up.

224
00:16:36,769 --> 00:16:38,759
Would you like your Twinkie now?

225
00:16:53,609 --> 00:16:54,758
Charlie?

226
00:16:57,089 --> 00:16:59,080
I want to suck your blood!

227
00:17:00,408 --> 00:17:02,524
I also want to suck your Twinkie!

228
00:17:03,009 --> 00:17:06,240
- Am I dead?
- No. You are the undead.

229
00:17:08,808 --> 00:17:11,084
Let's have it. You hate them, anyway.

230
00:17:11,449 --> 00:17:14,406
Young man! You stop that!

231
00:17:14,568 --> 00:17:18,448
Hey, I just made a deposit in your bank.
Now I want to make a withdrawal.

232
00:17:18,528 --> 00:17:20,804
I think it's time for your next class.

233
00:17:21,169 --> 00:17:24,844
- Go on! All of you!
- I'm a little worried about the side effects.

234
00:17:26,568 --> 00:17:28,525
Now, you lie back down.

235
00:17:31,929 --> 00:17:33,248
What am I doing here?

236
00:17:33,328 --> 00:17:36,401
You passed out for a minute, that's all.
Nothing to worry about.

237
00:17:36,489 --> 00:17:40,925
- But how did I get here?
- Why don't you let your friends help you?

238
00:17:41,048 --> 00:17:45,565
Take her into the washroom
and splash some cold water on her face...

239
00:17:45,648 --> 00:17:48,367
...and that should perk her up.
- Yes, ma'am.

240
00:17:48,528 --> 00:17:49,928
How are you doing?

241
00:17:53,648 --> 00:17:56,721
Blood drive? 1960?

242
00:18:00,888 --> 00:18:01,958
Wanna smoke?

243
00:18:02,048 --> 00:18:04,438
No, Carol. That's the worst thing for her.

244
00:18:04,528 --> 00:18:06,247
I gave them up years ago.

245
00:18:08,648 --> 00:18:11,242
- Where is it?
- Where's what?

246
00:18:13,409 --> 00:18:15,479
Maddy, what did you do to your hair?

247
00:18:17,328 --> 00:18:19,365
I'm taking you back to the nurse.

248
00:18:23,848 --> 00:18:27,318
- Delores, why aren't you giving blood?
- I can't. I'm too anaemic.

249
00:18:27,409 --> 00:18:29,604
Maybe you should drink
some of that nail polish.

250
00:18:29,689 --> 00:18:30,804
It might give you strength.

251
00:18:30,888 --> 00:18:33,198
Why don't you come back
and show me how?

252
00:18:40,608 --> 00:18:42,326
We're going to take you home now.

253
00:18:42,409 --> 00:18:45,401
That's okay.
I'm sure I can remember the way.

254
00:18:52,048 --> 00:18:53,402
Steady now.

255
00:18:55,288 --> 00:18:57,007
People get weak when they give blood.

256
00:19:19,808 --> 00:19:21,640
It's wonderful Spring Radio.

257
00:19:21,729 --> 00:19:26,007
At 1280 on your AM dial,
here's more from our golden survey.

258
00:19:28,769 --> 00:19:32,125
And now from The Champs,
let's party with a little Tequila.

259
00:19:56,929 --> 00:20:00,443
- I'll call you later.
- Yes! Let's keep in touch.

260
00:20:36,209 --> 00:20:37,528
Who is it?

261
00:20:38,328 --> 00:20:41,162
Peggy. Peggy Sue.

262
00:20:41,689 --> 00:20:44,521
Come on in. I left the door open for you.

263
00:20:59,449 --> 00:21:02,042
The nurse called
and said you'd be coming home.

264
00:21:02,209 --> 00:21:03,561
I have a note.

265
00:21:05,608 --> 00:21:09,363
- How do you feel?
- I was excused.

266
00:21:09,888 --> 00:21:12,642
Why don't you go upstairs
and lie down for a while?

267
00:21:14,088 --> 00:21:15,965
Oh, Mom!

268
00:21:17,769 --> 00:21:21,557
Chanel No. 5.
It always reminds me of home.

269
00:21:21,648 --> 00:21:24,083
Of course, dear. You're home now.

270
00:21:26,288 --> 00:21:29,804
- You sure you're going to be all right?
- Yeah.

271
00:22:21,048 --> 00:22:23,039
What is going on?

272
00:22:28,648 --> 00:22:29,637
Nancy?

273
00:22:30,689 --> 00:22:32,599
It's Nancy!

274
00:22:35,409 --> 00:22:37,763
My baby sister!

275
00:22:43,808 --> 00:22:47,563
- I'm so happy to see you!
- What are you doing?

276
00:22:48,088 --> 00:22:51,479
Mom said you were sick.
You're never happy to see me.

277
00:22:51,568 --> 00:22:54,527
I'm sorry! I'm sorry about that.

278
00:22:55,368 --> 00:22:57,200
I want us to be closer.

279
00:22:57,409 --> 00:23:00,526
I have too many unresolved relationships
in my life.

280
00:23:01,169 --> 00:23:04,047
Teenagers are weird.
And you're the weirdest.

281
00:23:07,368 --> 00:23:09,519
You wanna play a game?

282
00:23:09,689 --> 00:23:11,041
Come here.

283
00:23:12,648 --> 00:23:15,209
How about Monopoly?

284
00:23:15,288 --> 00:23:19,839
Or Parcheesi. Or Chutes and Ladders?

285
00:23:20,769 --> 00:23:22,963
I have a question.
Let me turn the tables on you.

286
00:23:23,048 --> 00:23:24,528
Maybe you, down here, don't know.

287
00:23:24,608 --> 00:23:28,284
Is there anybody in the house knows
where Dion and the Belmonts are?

288
00:23:29,608 --> 00:23:32,567
I don't believe it.
Look at that man. He never ages.

289
00:23:32,808 --> 00:23:34,845
Isn't Kenny Rossi dreamy?

290
00:23:35,368 --> 00:23:38,805
I wish he'd break up with Arlene.
She thinks she's so great.

291
00:23:39,689 --> 00:23:42,806
- Don't eat any of the red ones.
- Why not?

292
00:23:42,888 --> 00:23:47,883
They're bad for you.
They give you red lips.

293
00:24:09,848 --> 00:24:12,363
What the hell? I'm probably dead anyway.

294
00:24:12,568 --> 00:24:15,799
Peggy Sue, get in here!
Dion's almost over.

295
00:24:25,048 --> 00:24:28,564
I left your laundry on your beds, girls.
Don't forget to put it away, okay?

296
00:24:28,648 --> 00:24:29,876
What's for dinner?

297
00:24:29,969 --> 00:24:32,038
Creamed chipped beef on toast
with rutabagas.

298
00:24:32,128 --> 00:24:33,846
Your father's favourite.

299
00:24:34,088 --> 00:24:36,045
Not again!

300
00:24:36,568 --> 00:24:39,208
Evelyn! Girls?
What is this out on the street?

301
00:24:39,808 --> 00:24:41,878
Come and take a look!
Who left this out here?

302
00:24:41,969 --> 00:24:44,881
- What is it, dear?
- Come on out and see for yourself!

303
00:24:44,969 --> 00:24:46,321
Don't yell. Stop shouting.

304
00:24:50,608 --> 00:24:52,122
It's cool!

305
00:24:55,209 --> 00:24:57,483
- Dad!
- Wait until I tell Diane.

306
00:24:57,568 --> 00:25:00,128
She's always bragging
about her dad's Cadillac.

307
00:25:00,209 --> 00:25:01,961
What do you think, Peggy Sue?

308
00:25:02,048 --> 00:25:07,042
Oh, Dad! You were always doing
stuff like that! It's funny.

309
00:25:07,288 --> 00:25:11,601
It's really funny. You bought an Edsel.

310
00:25:13,808 --> 00:25:16,084
Young lady, what's the matter with you?

311
00:25:17,009 --> 00:25:18,202
Are you drunk?

312
00:25:20,409 --> 00:25:23,765
Just a little. I had a tough day.

313
00:25:27,288 --> 00:25:29,483
No, don't wear it out, Nancy!

314
00:25:30,449 --> 00:25:33,599
We can't afford a new car.
Do we have to take it back?

315
00:25:34,288 --> 00:25:37,598
I fail to see the humour of this!
Go to your room, you're grounded!

316
00:25:37,689 --> 00:25:40,282
- Grounded?
- Put that down!

317
00:25:40,808 --> 00:25:43,481
That's the story of my life! I'm an adult.

318
00:25:43,608 --> 00:25:46,123
I'm going to go to Liverpool
and discover The Beatles.

319
00:25:46,209 --> 00:25:49,041
Jack, take it easy!
She gave blood at school today.

320
00:25:49,128 --> 00:25:53,041
- She's a little lightheaded.
- This is not giving blood! This is drunk!

321
00:25:54,009 --> 00:25:56,886
Dad, I never knew you had
a sense of humour.

322
00:25:57,009 --> 00:25:59,647
- Evelyn, put her to bed!
- Come on, Mom!

323
00:25:59,769 --> 00:26:01,963
You're making a mountain
out of a molehill.

324
00:26:02,048 --> 00:26:03,561
A tempest in a teapot!

325
00:26:05,528 --> 00:26:07,086
My little baby.

326
00:26:13,449 --> 00:26:15,359
Don't try to grow up so fast.

327
00:26:17,528 --> 00:26:19,837
Mom, I forgot you were ever this young.

328
00:26:20,929 --> 00:26:22,327
Sleep, baby.

329
00:26:46,969 --> 00:26:48,084
Good morning.

330
00:26:48,169 --> 00:26:52,480
What happened to your hair, Peggy?
You have such a pretty face.

331
00:26:52,689 --> 00:26:55,920
- Why are you always trying to cover it up?
- I forgot.

332
00:26:56,489 --> 00:26:58,047
- 'Morning.
- 'Morning.

333
00:26:58,769 --> 00:26:59,837
Excuse me.

334
00:26:59,929 --> 00:27:02,886
Nancy, put your homework down
and sit down.

335
00:27:04,489 --> 00:27:06,719
You're looking bright and chipper
this morning.

336
00:27:06,808 --> 00:27:10,118
I'm still here.
I thought I might as well enjoy myself.

337
00:27:10,209 --> 00:27:12,200
I think I'll go to school today.

338
00:27:12,848 --> 00:27:15,965
You know, Dad, I'm sorry about yesterday.

339
00:27:16,929 --> 00:27:20,365
The Edsel is a classic.
Use it in the best of health.

340
00:27:20,449 --> 00:27:21,768
Well, thank you.

341
00:27:21,969 --> 00:27:24,801
But don't ever let anything
like that happen again.

342
00:27:24,888 --> 00:27:28,006
You're far too young
to start acquiring bad habits.

343
00:27:28,409 --> 00:27:30,479
I agree. You know, Mom and Dad...

344
00:27:31,368 --> 00:27:34,759
...you are the best parents
a girl could ever have.

345
00:27:35,689 --> 00:27:37,963
I'm really gonna try and behave myself.

346
00:27:38,249 --> 00:27:39,728
Sure you will!

347
00:27:42,009 --> 00:27:43,646
Come on, Momma, sit down.

348
00:27:44,568 --> 00:27:46,082
You want me to sit?

349
00:27:46,568 --> 00:27:50,198
I mean, isn't this great?
Just all of us here together!

350
00:27:54,368 --> 00:27:56,836
Can I tell Charlie
Peggy Sue got drunk last night?

351
00:27:56,929 --> 00:27:58,044
Young lady!

352
00:27:59,249 --> 00:28:02,161
I forgot about him. What am I gonna do?

353
00:28:02,328 --> 00:28:04,923
- Did you two have a fight?
- Sort of.

354
00:28:05,009 --> 00:28:06,806
- About what?
- House payments.

355
00:28:11,848 --> 00:28:12,998
Baby!

356
00:28:14,169 --> 00:28:15,488
How do you feel?

357
00:28:16,288 --> 00:28:17,801
Pretty strange.

358
00:28:18,489 --> 00:28:21,162
Come on. Get in. I can take care of that.

359
00:28:25,288 --> 00:28:26,688
I have a headache.

360
00:28:28,568 --> 00:28:30,126
Headache?

361
00:28:35,888 --> 00:28:37,527
You drive like a maniac!

362
00:28:40,409 --> 00:28:42,319
It's not that I'm glad you were sick...

363
00:28:42,409 --> 00:28:46,163
...but it just gave me a chance
to do some thinking last night.

364
00:28:46,249 --> 00:28:50,560
- Yeah?
- Yeah. About what we said on Tuesday.

365
00:28:51,249 --> 00:28:53,365
I think it makes a lot of sense.

366
00:28:54,449 --> 00:28:57,486
- Refresh my memory.
- How could you forget?

367
00:28:57,848 --> 00:29:01,000
We talk about seeing other people
and you forget.

368
00:29:02,848 --> 00:29:05,157
I must have blocked it out.

369
00:29:07,169 --> 00:29:10,479
Yeah. I guess I can understand that.

370
00:29:11,929 --> 00:29:15,318
But, please, don't start crying again.

371
00:29:25,249 --> 00:29:26,967
It's not gonna be forever.

372
00:29:27,048 --> 00:29:32,327
I figure three years is long enough
for the music to pan out, which it will.

373
00:29:32,648 --> 00:29:33,968
I know it.

374
00:29:34,169 --> 00:29:36,842
So right after graduation we should...

375
00:29:36,929 --> 00:29:40,079
...one: Start to see other people
so that we can...

376
00:29:40,368 --> 00:29:42,929
...two: We can comparison-shop.

377
00:29:43,648 --> 00:29:46,959
And then, three:
Settle down and get married.

378
00:29:49,608 --> 00:29:52,567
Why wait? Why not break up now?

379
00:29:53,848 --> 00:29:57,842
Because we got the prom coming up
and all these parties.

380
00:29:58,088 --> 00:30:01,763
- We don't want to upset our parents.
- They'll learn to live with it.

381
00:30:28,209 --> 00:30:29,278
Peggy Sue!

382
00:30:38,368 --> 00:30:41,361
Peggy Sue, come here.

383
00:30:55,209 --> 00:30:56,278
Peggy Sue.

384
00:30:56,929 --> 00:30:58,601
Did you study for the test?

385
00:30:58,689 --> 00:31:02,364
- Test? There's a test?
- Yeah.

386
00:31:12,209 --> 00:31:14,244
All right, class. Time's up.

387
00:31:23,929 --> 00:31:26,363
And what's the meaning of this,
Peggy Sue?

388
00:31:27,169 --> 00:31:29,046
Mr. Snelgrove...

389
00:31:29,489 --> 00:31:33,277
...I happen to know that in the future
I will have no use for algebra.

390
00:31:33,368 --> 00:31:35,165
And I speak from experience.

391
00:31:38,368 --> 00:31:39,961
- Who said that?
- I'm sorry.

392
00:31:40,048 --> 00:31:41,038
Sit down!

393
00:31:41,209 --> 00:31:45,361
The result of his struggle is
that Santiago comes back with honour.

394
00:31:45,449 --> 00:31:47,837
Santiago comes back with nothing!

395
00:31:48,288 --> 00:31:50,086
There's no meat on the bone.

396
00:31:50,169 --> 00:31:52,842
It's Hemingway's ego
trying to defend itself again.

397
00:31:52,929 --> 00:31:55,124
Trying to prove he can still perform.

398
00:31:55,209 --> 00:31:58,758
What Hemingway's saying, Michael,
is that we are alone.

399
00:31:58,848 --> 00:32:01,488
That when we go out too far,
we're vulnerable.

400
00:32:01,848 --> 00:32:05,159
The irony that Santiago
is beaten by the sharks...

401
00:32:05,608 --> 00:32:07,724
...doesn't make him less of a hero.

402
00:32:07,848 --> 00:32:10,238
Who is the victim and who is the predator?

403
00:32:12,848 --> 00:32:14,919
We'll finish this discussion next week.

404
00:32:15,009 --> 00:32:18,922
And don't forget, first four chapters
of The Great Gatsby by Monday.

405
00:32:19,328 --> 00:32:20,807
Hope you enjoy it.

406
00:32:30,048 --> 00:32:32,801
Why does your father take inventory
on Sunday nights?

407
00:32:32,888 --> 00:32:34,038
Hi, Peggy.

408
00:32:34,128 --> 00:32:37,359
It's poker night.
You always got out of it before.

409
00:32:37,449 --> 00:32:40,998
I just gotta string him along for a while.
It's for his own good.

410
00:32:41,088 --> 00:32:44,398
You're not going into his business.
When are you gonna tell him?

411
00:32:44,489 --> 00:32:45,398
Soon.

412
00:32:48,769 --> 00:32:49,484
Walter!

413
00:32:49,568 --> 00:32:51,763
I can't tell everybody everything
all at once.

414
00:32:51,848 --> 00:32:54,602
Strange rumours
are sweeping the school about you.

415
00:32:54,689 --> 00:32:56,008
Hi, Peggy.

416
00:32:56,088 --> 00:32:57,203
What do you mean?

417
00:32:57,288 --> 00:33:01,680
- I hear you gave it to old Smellygrove.
- I was there! She told him off to his face!

418
00:33:01,769 --> 00:33:02,917
Attagirl, Peg!

419
00:33:03,009 --> 00:33:04,760
Arthur, please don't call me Peg.

420
00:33:04,848 --> 00:33:06,362
"Why, I oughta..."

421
00:33:09,128 --> 00:33:10,084
I don't get it.

422
00:33:10,169 --> 00:33:12,557
That's 'cause you're not
a total moron like they are.

423
00:33:12,648 --> 00:33:14,445
It's a stupid movie thing they started.

424
00:33:14,528 --> 00:33:16,440
That's enough outta you, little lady!

425
00:33:19,449 --> 00:33:20,961
"Why, I oughta..."

426
00:33:23,808 --> 00:33:25,321
I'll be right back.

427
00:33:30,169 --> 00:33:31,727
Hi, Richard.

428
00:33:32,929 --> 00:33:36,079
I wanted to congratulate you
on winning the math contest.

429
00:33:36,608 --> 00:33:38,280
It really wasn't that difficult.

430
00:33:38,368 --> 00:33:41,679
What are you doing?
You fishing for four-eyed worms?

431
00:33:42,368 --> 00:33:44,404
Get lost, you macho schmuck!

432
00:33:48,449 --> 00:33:51,486
I wanted to talk to you.
It's really important.

433
00:33:52,088 --> 00:33:54,603
I'm not doing any tutoring this year.
I'm too busy.

434
00:33:54,689 --> 00:33:56,644
No, it's not about that.

435
00:33:56,888 --> 00:33:59,356
Would you meet me after school, please?

436
00:34:02,808 --> 00:34:05,606
All right. I'll be in the physics lab.

437
00:34:08,768 --> 00:34:11,442
Make it 4:30.
I have to go to a Rocket Club meeting.

438
00:34:11,528 --> 00:34:12,358
Sure.

439
00:34:18,128 --> 00:34:19,880
She's not wasting any time.

440
00:34:20,009 --> 00:34:23,684
- Peggy Sue and Mr. Square Root.
- He's a nice guy. He's writing a book.

441
00:34:23,969 --> 00:34:26,802
A book? Excuse me for a second.

442
00:34:28,289 --> 00:34:30,007
Why is she punishing herself?

443
00:34:50,929 --> 00:34:54,637
Come on, Peggy Sue. Try it again.
You haven't been practising.

444
00:34:54,728 --> 00:34:55,878
Sorry.

445
00:34:55,969 --> 00:34:58,766
What a girl, what a twirl.
Peg "Leggy" Sue Kelcher.

446
00:34:58,849 --> 00:35:01,760
A brief but glorious career as a majorette.

447
00:35:04,248 --> 00:35:05,159
Baby!

448
00:35:08,809 --> 00:35:10,447
Looking good out there!

449
00:35:10,688 --> 00:35:11,643
Thanks.

450
00:35:16,449 --> 00:35:18,643
I love it when you twirl your baton.

451
00:35:22,128 --> 00:35:25,360
I noticed you were giving me
the silent treatment at lunch.

452
00:35:26,648 --> 00:35:28,206
I guess I deserved it.

453
00:35:28,329 --> 00:35:30,842
I've been thinking
about my three-year plan.

454
00:35:30,969 --> 00:35:34,757
I think it's totally unworkable.
I must have been delirious.

455
00:35:36,009 --> 00:35:38,284
I don't know.
I thought it made some sense.

456
00:35:38,369 --> 00:35:42,043
Well, in the abstract, maybe.
Get a good grip on yourself.

457
00:35:44,048 --> 00:35:48,440
When I think about you going out
with other guys, I feel...

458
00:35:49,648 --> 00:35:52,800
Rejected? Worthless? Miserable?

459
00:35:54,849 --> 00:35:55,963
Yeah.

460
00:35:57,449 --> 00:35:58,563
Good.

461
00:36:21,009 --> 00:36:22,282
Boy, that's some kite!

462
00:36:22,489 --> 00:36:24,878
I'm writing a book on kite construction.

463
00:36:25,449 --> 00:36:27,405
So what do you wanna talk about?

464
00:36:28,449 --> 00:36:30,565
I just wanted to ask you a question.

465
00:36:33,208 --> 00:36:35,768
Do you think time travel is possible?

466
00:36:38,208 --> 00:36:41,326
- Are you doing a science project?
- Sort of.

467
00:36:43,369 --> 00:36:46,360
Well, that's a very interesting question.

468
00:36:46,889 --> 00:36:48,163
Well, now, let's see.

469
00:36:48,248 --> 00:36:51,559
If we look at this
in a Newtonian framework...

470
00:36:52,128 --> 00:36:54,882
...the possibilities of time travel
were limited.

471
00:36:55,248 --> 00:36:59,128
With the advent of the relativity theory,
that's Einstein's relativity theory...

472
00:36:59,208 --> 00:37:02,201
...the idea of absolute time
cannot be reasonably affirmed.

473
00:37:03,489 --> 00:37:06,083
Well, then we have Richard's burrito.

474
00:37:07,409 --> 00:37:08,318
What's that?

475
00:37:08,409 --> 00:37:11,639
That's my own theory,
based on a Mexican food called the burrito.

476
00:37:11,809 --> 00:37:15,483
- I had one at Disneyland.
- I know what a burrito is!

477
00:37:16,568 --> 00:37:19,527
You see, I think that time is like a burrito...

478
00:37:20,329 --> 00:37:23,445
...in the sense that one part of itself
will fold over...

479
00:37:23,528 --> 00:37:26,362
...and it will just touch the other part.

480
00:37:26,889 --> 00:37:29,925
- What's inside?
- You can fill it with whatever you want.

481
00:37:30,009 --> 00:37:34,480
You can fill it with memories,
with experiences, trigonometry. Anything.

482
00:37:35,889 --> 00:37:39,358
Then you think
that time travel is possible for people?

483
00:37:39,528 --> 00:37:41,679
Yes, it is. It is possible.

484
00:37:42,329 --> 00:37:46,766
It's absolutely possible for people,
dogs, elephants, cancan girls.

485
00:37:47,608 --> 00:37:49,088
Then I'm not crazy!

486
00:37:50,728 --> 00:37:52,878
I really don't know if you're crazy.

487
00:37:53,489 --> 00:37:55,400
I know most people think I am.

488
00:37:58,248 --> 00:37:59,601
- Come here, Richard.
- What?

489
00:37:59,688 --> 00:38:01,407
- Come on.
- What are you doing?

490
00:38:01,489 --> 00:38:03,240
Wait a minute, what are you...

